InterSystems HealthShare Health Data De-Identifier

Overview

InterSystems HealthShare Health Data De-Identifier is a customizable SDA to SDA de-identification application with out-of-the-box support for HIPAA Safe Harbor §164.514(b)(2), date shifting and re-identification.

SDA (Summary Document Architecture) is the central piece of patient data representation across InterSystems IRIS for Health and several HealthShare products. As transformations across standards can be extremely hard and time consuming due to the number of existing ones and versions out there, SDA helps bridge this many-to-many relationship.
In addition to helping the interoperability aspect, having the SDA as common factor makes it special when handling de-identification. Instead of having to worry how to apply de-identification rules on top of several standards, data can be received in its original format, de-identified during the transformation process and then sent to its target. For more, Summary Document Architecture (SDA) documentation.

SDA can be represented and transported as XML, with that, Health Data De-ID leverages the performance and reliability of XSLT transformations to do the de-identification process. Helper methods allow for complex and granular manipulation of the SDA XML structure. Customization or extensions to the existing HIPAA Safe Harbor support can be done by changing the XSLT template or customizing the helper methods. To know more about general XSLT transformation, Performing XSLT Transformations documentation.

Health Data De-ID is deployed on InterSystems IRIS for Health Community Edition, therefore, limitations applied to the community edition are also applied to Health Data De-ID. To know more, InterSystems IRIS Community Edition Limitations.
Having InterSystems IRIS for Health Community Edition as the version of deployment also means that Health Data De-ID is provided as a Docker image.

If you are not familiar with containers, you can find more information:

  • Deploy in Containers
  • Hands-On with Docker Containers

Health Data De-ID

Health Data De-ID leverages InterSystems IRIS interoperability capabilities to allow ingestion of health data in virtually any format one needs. After the proper transformation (when applicable) from the outbound format into SDA, Health Data De-ID can be plugged into the pipeline to apply de-identification and again leverage InterSystems IRIS interoperability to send the information to any downstream systems.

Also for special cases, Health Data De-ID can leverage the same set of XSLT transformations and helper methods to process native HealthShare Health Insight Persistent Request messages.

The Environment

This evaluation has available a sample production with built-in components for HL7, SDA and PR processing.

For better reliability when evaluating Health Data De-ID, using SDA or PR XML files as input is highly recommended (more details about how to input files below). In case you want to process HL7, Health Data De-ID has two HL7 services that applies standard HealthShare HL7 to SDA transformation. These services are available as file and TCP inbound.

Health Data De-ID provides an UI to help upload SDA, HL7 and PR files and check the differences between the input and output.

Note: HL7 services were provided for convenience, any special transformations from HL7 to SDA or any other format to SDA have to be created by the evaluator.

Starting

First download the files that will be required for your environment.

  • project.zip
  • one of both depending on your architecture:
    • evaluation.amd64.tar.gz
    • evaluation.arm64v8.tar.gz

After you have downloaded, unzip project.zip and open a terminal of your choosing and navigate where the files were downloaded.

Example: cd c:\tmp or cd /tmp/

1) Load image (should take a couple of minutes)

# depending on your architecture:

# amd64
docker load -i evaluation.amd64.tar.gz

# arm64v8
docker load -i evaluation.arm64v8.tar.gz

2) Check the image was properly loaded

docker images

# example of output (IDs may vary)
REPOSITORY                                       TAG               IMAGE ID       CREATED         SIZE
intersystems/evaluation/health-data-deid         latest            d7278c2228bd   2 hours ago     4.79GB

3) From the terminal, go to the project directory you unzipped.

docker compose up -d

# output
[+] Running 2/2
✔ Network project_default  Created                                        0.0s
✔ Container xid            Started                                        0.3s

EXTRA: To reset your evaluation environment (if needed)

docker compose down    # kills the container
docker compose up -d

Starting InterSystems IRIS (should take around 30 seconds)

4) Now that InterSystems IRIS is up and running, you can access the System Management Portal (SMP) through http://localhost:52773/csp/sys/%25CSP.Portal.Home.zen.

The default credentials are:

  • Username: evaluation
  • Password: SYS

You will be asked to enter a new set of credentials, go ahead and choose any credentials you wish.

Welcome to Health Data De-ID.

Using

After you gain access to the SMP, you should notice a few things:

1) There is a dedicate menu on the left side to access the Health Data De-ID UI.
2) The pre-configured production is already up and running.
3) The main namespace Health Data De-ID is running is XID.

Basic: De-identifying SDA (or HL7) through the UI

On the SMP, click on Health Data De-ID (1).

In here you have four buttons:

1) Load SDA: Helper to upload SDA files in XML format. (NOTE: the file must have xml as extension)
2) Load PR: Helper to upload Health Insight Persistent Request files. (NOTE: the file must have xml as extension)
3) Load HL7: Helper to upload HL7 files. (NOTE: the file must have hl7 as extension)
4) Production: Shortcut to InterSystems IRIS Interoperability production.

Click on either Load SDA, Load PR or Load HL7. On the first window you can either drag & drop you file or select it using the Select file button.
Once you have loaded the file, a Done! message will appear. You can click Close.

Step 1 Step 2

Now that the file is loaded you can see it on the main UI. (NOTE: this list will show the last 10 messages that when through the de-identification process, regardless of the input method)

On the list you have 5 columns:

1) TRACE: Shows the file name (where applicable) and link to Message Trace.

2) ORIGINAL: Shows the raw input SDA. (NOTE: If the initial input is anything other than SDA this will still show the SDA that triggered the de-identification process)

3) DE-IDENTIFIED: Shows the raw output SDA. (similar output to above)
4) DIFF: In-screen diff against ORIGINAL and DE-IDENTIFIED files. (this can take a few seconds to run)

5) SDA STATS: Runs an extract of simple stats on the differences between the ORIGINAL and DE-IDENTIFIED files and output to CSV (not available for PR).

The comparison CSV file is another way to see the differences between the ORIGINAL and DE-IDENTIFIED files.

1) Flattened SDA path;
2) Old value;
3) New value;
4) If the value is removed, [dropped] will be set as New value;
5) If the value is unchanged, [same] will be set as New value;
6) Any other changed values.

Totals of changed, dropped and same values are summarized the the bottom of the file.

Advanced

There are several ways to harness the power of Health Data De-ID, this document will outline a couple of options.

Customizing docker compose (using file inbound)

This project is meant to work without any changes to the docker compose.yml file. However, changes can be made to adapt the evaluation to more specific scenarios. Examples are where specific ports are required, or changing the mounting volumes.

Below is a sample customization of the docker compose.yml file where InterSystems IRIS ports where changed on the host side (NOTE: InterSystems IRIS ports on the container side should not be changed; TCP ports can be changed on both sides, but the production must reflect any changes made). Also changes to the host path (source) on the volumes were made (NOTE: Paths in this sample are not real)

version: '3.7'
services:
  xid:
    image: intersystems/evaluation/health-data-deid:latest
    init: true
    hostname: xid
    container_name: xid
    restart: "no"
    ports:
      - "9091:1972"        # [host:container] Default InterSystems IRIS superserver port; can be changed as needed.
      - "9092:52773"       # [host:container] Default InterSystems IRIS web port; can be changed as needed.
      - "9901:9901"        # [host:container] HL7 Inbound TCP port; can be changed as needed.
    volumes:
    - type: bind
      source: ./external/XID        # Where the XSLT file resides on the host, changing the file will affect the container.
      target: /data/xslt/SDA3/XID   # [INTERNAL - DO NOT CHANGE]
    - type: bind
      source: ./my/own/path/SDAIn   # SDA file inbound on the host; can be changed as needed.
      target: /data/SDAIn           # [INTERNAL - DO NOT CHANGE]
    - type: bind
      source: ./my/own/path/HL7In   # HL7 file inbound on the host; can be changed as needed.
      target: /data/HL7In           # [INTERNAL - DO NOT CHANGE]
    - type: bind
      source: ./my/own/path/SDAOut  # SDA file outbound on the host; can be changed as needed.
      target: /data/SDAOut          # [INTERNAL - DO NOT CHANGE]
    - type: bind
      source: ./external/PRIn       # PR file inbound on the host; can be changed as needed.
      target: /data/PRIn            # [INTERNAL - DO NOT CHANGE]
    - type: bind
      source: ./external/PROut      # PR file outbound on the host; can be changed as needed.
      target: /data/PROut           # [INTERNAL - DO NOT CHANGE]

Expanding a little more on the volumes, if you wish to load several files at once, the you can use the specific volume mounts for each type: SDA (SDAIn), PR (PRIn) and HL7 (HL7In).
Dropping files on the host path for any of the types will allow the production to pick them up and process them as same as it did via the UI. Note that same restrictions apply: SDA and PR must have xml extension (mySDA.xml or myPR.xml) and HL7 must have hl7 extension (myHL7.hl7).

After the files are processed you can see the entries on the UI and use the diff tools available. (NOTE: last 10 messages)

Customizing XSLT transformations (and helper methods)

XSLT transformation is a vast topic on its own, details of it will not be covered in this section. To know more about general XSLT transformation, Performing XSLT Transformations documentation.

Once you start the container, the actual XSLT file used by Health Data De-ID will be created into [project-root-directory]/external/XID/DeIDTransform.xsl, and it should be similar to the below:

<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>
<xsl:stylesheet xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xmlns:xsl="http://www.w3.org/1999/XSL/Transform" xmlns:isc="http://extension-functions.intersystems.com" exclude-result-prefixes="xsi isc" version="1.0">
<xsl:output method="xml" indent="yes" encoding="ISO-8859-1" omit-xml-declaration="yes"/>
<xsl:strip-space elements="*"/>

<xsl:template match="@* | node()">
    <xsl:copy>
        <xsl:apply-templates select="@* | node()"/>
    </xsl:copy>
</xsl:template>

<!-- Sending Facility transformation is there for testing purposes-->
<xsl:template match="SendingFacility">
<xsl:variable name="SendingFacility" select="/SendingFacility/text()"/>
<SendingFacility>
<!--xsl:value-of select="isc:evaluate('piece',/SendingFacility/text(),'A',1)"/-->
<xsl:variable name="child" select="name(./*[1]) != ''"/>
<xsl:value-of select="isc:evaluate('XIDtest',text())"/>
</SendingFacility>
</xsl:template>
...

This file can be modified to accommodate any custom needs beyond HIPAA Safe Harbor §164.514(b)(2).

Say you want to encrypt the diagnosis code. There are two steps required:

1) Modify the XSLT.
Add to the end of [project-root-directory]/external/XID/DeIDTransform.xsl. The code is in between the NoteId match and the closing stylesheet.

...
<xsl:template match="NoteId">
<xsl:variable name="child" select="name(./*[1]) != ''"/>
<xsl:value-of disable-output-escaping="yes" select="isc:evaluate('XIDidentifyingnumber',$child,text(),name())"/>
</xsl:template>

<!--
    This is my custom entry where I am sending the diagnosis code of the SDA to my custom method XIDcustomdiagnosis (method will be created below). 
-->
<xsl:template match="Diagnosis/Code">
<xsl:variable name="child" select="name(./*[1]) != ''"/>
<xsl:value-of disable-output-escaping="yes" select="isc:evaluate('XIDcustomdiagnosis',$child,text(),name())"/>
</xsl:template>
<!-- end custom -->

<!--
(K) Certificate/license numbers
-->

</xsl:stylesheet>

2) Create XIDcustomdiagnosis method.
Using your preferred IDE, go to XID namespace and open HS.Local.XID.XSLTHelper class.

/// XSLT helper class for de-identification transformations HIPAA Safe Harbor.
/// This class is used on conjunction with the XSLT transformation provided.
/// For customizations overwrite extended method from XID.Production.Transformation.XSLTHelper.
Class HS.Local.XID.XSLTHelper Extends XID.Production.Transformation.XSLTHelper
{

///  Example of removing gender customization
/// 
/// This would have to be added to the XSLT
///     <xsl:template match="Gender">
///     <xsl:variable name="child" select="name(./*[1]) != ''"/>
///     <xsl:value-of disable-output-escaping="yes" select="isc:evaluate('XIDgender',$child,text(),name())"/>
///     </xsl:template>
Method XIDgender(child As %Boolean, value As %String, tagname As %String) As %String
{
    return ""
}

/// Manipulate patient name (example of customization 1)
/// 
/// Because NAMEs have sub-nodes and the main method returns the full tag, in this example, the parent method is executed and 
/// further manipulation is done by replacing the content within tag (as the parent method already returned the full tag)
Method XIDname(child As %Boolean, value As %String, tagname As %String) As %String
{
    set ret = ##super(child,value,tagname)
    set name = $piece($piece(ret,"<GivenName>",2),"</GivenName>",1)
    set ret = $replace(ret,name,"DEID:"_name)
    return ret
}
...

Add the method below and compile:

/// This is my custom diagnosis method. It just creates a Code tab with the original value encrypted and prefix it with MyCustom:
Method XIDcustomdiagnosis(child As %Boolean, value As %String, tagname As %String) As %String
{
    return "<Code>MyCustom:"_$System.Encryption.Base64Encode($System.Encryption.GenCryptRand(6)_"</Code>"
}

You can now load data using your preferred mechanism (or use unit-test.* file provided). You can confirm that the change is in full effect.

Customizations can be done also by extending the existing methods in HS.Local.XID.XSLTHelper. A sample of how it can be done is already implemented in the class on the method XIDname.
